Technological determinism is a concept that included, pragmatically, a wide range of ideas, from the technological impulse or imperative to a strict sense that there is an underlying logic that drives the fate of mankind and that is related to the laws of science and how it is embodied in technology.
Almost all interpretations of technological determinism have two general ideas in common: that technological development in itself unfolds on a path independent of any cultural or political influence, and that, at the same time, technology has “effects” in societies that are inherently and non-social.
To give an example, one could argue that the existence of automobiles necessarily derive in road development.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a reduced volume of automobiles, with the result that new manufacturing techniques are being designed to reduce the costs of owning a vehicle.
Massive use of cars also generates a higher incidence of traffic accidents, leading to the development of new techniques in the health field to repair the damage to bodies.
